Absolutely! It makes your code cleaner, especially if you chain a bunch of operations like so:

```
let mut buffer = [0; 128];
let n = tokio::fs::File::open("data.bin")
    .await?
    .read(&mut buffer)
    .await?;
``` This way you can write code that looks synchronous but runs asynchronously, reducing the risk of blocking the runtime. Still, remember to avoid mixing async and non-async parts unless necessary.

Oh wait, I see you forgot to include the Tokio runtime. `reqwest` is async by design, so you need it for async tasks. Just add tokio as a dependency in your Cargo.toml:

```toml
[dependencies]
tokio = { version="1", features=["full"] }
reqwest = { version="0.11", features=["json"] }
```
Then initialize the Tokio runtime before calling `reqwest`. Here’s a quick snippet to get you started:

```rust
#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), reqwest::Error> {
    let response = reqwest::get("https://httpbin.org/ip").await?.text().await?;
    println!("Response: {response}");
    Ok(())
}
```
